Objects must compare equal to themselves. If you don&#39;t add this first check, it&#39;s surprisingly easy for an object to not compare equal to itself. Typically, this can happen if you have a `float` or `double` field.

For example, if `X` is a class with a double field `f`, then this code is WRONG, because it violates the reflexive rule of equality:
 
    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object o){
        if(!(o instanceof X))
           return false;
       X x = (X)o;
       return f == x.f;
    }

If you compare an object with `f=Double.NaN` to itself, it will return false -- because NaN does not compare equal to itself.

